	</div><div class="blogs_entrybody" style="clear:both">
		Wally Wahlberg sat at his breakfast table in the luxurious Manhattan apartment that he shared with his wife and two daughters.  He had carefully placed himself at the table so that his back was towards the kitchen door.  It was his birthday and he knew that the kids had a surprise waiting for him.<br/><br/>"Happy birthday, daddy!" yelled the fair-haired duo as they placed a construction paper birthday card in front of him, narrowly missing his half-eaten eggs and toast.<br/><br/>Wally smiled and gave each of the girls a kiss. He enjoyed being a father and a husband more than anything in his life.  He glanced at his diamond-encrusted wristwatch and leapt from the table just as the familiar honk of the Lincoln town car blared outside the window.<br/><br/>"Daddy is late!  But I'll see you two princesses after work, okay?" Wally exclaimed as he ran out of the front door, nearly knocking his wife to the ground.<br/><br/>"Slow down there honey, you're going to hurt somebody!  Did you get the letter from...?" Wanda said as the front door closed in front of her.<br/><br/>"I guess not." she mumbled as she wandered into the kitchen to get the girls ready for their day at the local public elementary school.<br/><br/>*<br/><br/>"The lumbering ox just can't seem to meet market expectations." Sinjin said as he shook his head.  "I've been watching National Communicators for years, and these guys move slower than my grandmother after that folding couch accident." <br/><br/>Sinjin was the most senior of the equity analysts at EEE, and had an impeccable reputation in the financial markets.  If he so much as burped while talking about a company, their stock, or future projects, that company could find their stock trading at a much lower price the following day.  It was a lot of responsibility, but he was used to it.  He really was the best, but you'd never hear him bragging about it.<br/><br/>*beep*<br/><br/>The familiar and regularly bothersome beep of his Blackberry phone interrupted his thoughts.  He glanced at the screen to find a message from one of EEE's CEOs on his screen.<br/><br/>"My office.  Twenty minutes.  Don't be late. WW" <br/><br/>A stabbing pain went through Sinjin's stomach.  Was he in trouble?  Was he getting promoted?  Did Wally finally find out who had been sneaking into the executive washroom to enjoy the triple-ply bathroom tissue?  His hands began to shake as he put the Blackberry back into the case on his belt and looked around on his desk for his antacid tablets.<br/><br/>*<br/><br/>"Mr. Wreed, I'm a bit confused.  When we talked on the phone, you mentioned that there was some impropriety occurring amongst some staff members that involved financial matters.  You never touched on this." I said as I flipped over to a fresh page in my trusty notepad.<br/><br/>Wreed loosened his tie and sat back in his chair.  "I apologize, but a great deal of information has come to me since our conversation and the beginning of this engagement.   Allow me to explain."<br/><br/>"Please." I begged.<br/><br/>"Are you familiar with a company called National Communicators?" Wreed asked.<br/><br/>Scrap awoke from his nap and piped up.  "NC?  Those guys are into everything.  Cell phones, data services, dial tone, you name it." <br/><br/>"Very good, Mr. Scrap.  They are quite the behemoth.  They are so big, in fact, that the new executive team that was hired on a few months ago has had a very hard time steering them towards growth.  Their stock has been flat for years.  However, recently there has been a lot of communication between EEE and NC.  Well, there has been a lot of communication between Mr. Wahlberg and Mr. Whet, the CEO of NC.  I was astounded that Wahlberg would be attempting to get NC's business for our money management division without my knowledge and called him on it.  He told me that he and Whet are old college buddies and there was nothing to talk about." Wreed explained.<br/><br/>"I'm following you." I said.  "So where does this take us?"<br/><br/>Wreed sat up in his chair and threw his pen on his desk.<br/><br/>"I want you to find out what is really going on between Wahlberg and Whet, who on my staff is involved, and you need to do it quickly.  I firmly believe that Wahlberg is cooking up a deal that will eject me from the company and hurt a lot of other people in the process." Wreed said tensely.<br/><br/>"Like who?" Scrap asked.<br/><br/>"A few hundred thousand investors."<br/><br/><hr><br/><p><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20100710090115/http://www.numly.com/numly/verify.asp?id=33794-061227-255074-40"><img alt="numly esn" src="https://web.archive.org/web/20100710090115im_/http://numly.com/numly/icon.asp?id=3379406122725507440" border="0"> 33794-061227-255074-40<br><img src="https://web.archive.org/web/20100710090115im_/http://numly.com/numly/barcode.asp?code=3379406122725507440&amp;height=20&amp;width=1&amp;mode=code39"></a><br><br>© 2006 All Rights Reserved.</p><p><hr><table width="100%" bgcolor="#FFFFCC" cellpadding="9px">
<tr><td><img style="margin-right: 9px; float: left" src="https://web.archive.org/web/20100710090115im_/http://userimages.ittoolbox.com/user/s_610000.jpg"><b><font face="Arial" size="4">DID YOU KNOW?</b></font><font face="Arial" size="2"><p style="margin-top: 2px">You can read all of SecurityMonkey's case files! <br>Find them <b><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20100710090115/http://blogs.ittoolbox.com/security/investigator/archives/official-securitymonkey-case-file-index-14787">here</a></b>. <br><br>You can also read all of SecurityMonkey's <br>'Banana Cupboard' stories <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20100710090115/http://blogs.ittoolbox.com/security/investigator/archives/banana-cupboard-stories-index-25647">here</a>.  <br><br>You may not get a lot done for a few hours... or even days.</font><br><br>The reviews are in...<br><br><i>"Completely addictive... suspenseful and informative at the same time!"<br>"A mix of classic detective scripting, timing, and technology..."<br>"Cleverly injected humor makes these case files easy to read and hard to put down!"</i></td></tr></table><hr><p>
